[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring Scala visibility**\n\nI'm considering whether to test via `scalac`, even though I’m instructed not to compile or run tests. I want to understand the rules around private members in Scala. For instance, a private method like `foo` in class `C` doesn't get mangled. But if I have `private[C]`, could it become something like `C$$foo`? Hm, private to a class does allow access to the companion object, which complicates things. I should check with `javap` how access works under the hood.\n\n**Understanding method visibility in Scala**\n\nI’m thinking about how private methods in a class are accessed only by that class, so why would the compiler expand method names to something like `Foo$$method`? I've noticed with `javap` that private methods might show differently. Name expansion seems to prevent issues with overriding if a subclass has the same method name. I remember Scala compiles private methods with a prefix, like `C$$foo`, to avoid potential conflicts. It all connects with protecting method integrity in inheritance.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_00fbe55c2a84c5560169fa3c9254b48192bfe343377947aefa\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-jynb9JmNHLVlUSRqlkFQcL_Oo2PSF5aABBcXhmgtH6CzGAElGtlMnkXdTu7BQRjoDXavcZ0XrygWIjXHJvZdxIwH-NXofZfHWwLAzv_Vp5ikJ3fhGeem4ehTkEfkx8hMqfzSUvKnyQgKw_57pGCCyuPCLUl3zzTiGwW7bojrS0Ll1M91aCcySiXztxFkXy2bLRDPr68jfmN7WdVI4-dyD5NpBOZSsDUzfarVQjeun5Qgwb2HtDrupA4nSE3PM58yQssULjvJ_fWzWrJcHKmzThKVIYUyX2Ze1AuVnG-wWlaa9JiMV8JjZAXQKKfrhp1XKnxYjDAt4yPCCa87DOGcEuBaYKECXyO3FrR3YxQrKIW7_znyNV-r00eNpNftgYOvWEH8fRioaT_jBP9wfixuO2ghnBWoWWL2EjEBp9UBe7TPE5aHvspsswPH5HeTt23h541vu7SE_YPCsm2PiPlMcy1LW_Let_WBWT-DxIkzOwbfDAtrEBd5Tl0rLczEQCdC_B5pIAcIfYPOVPWoMk5Ge311EpPwMGh41lyiKR7iAsA4c00cF-W5jkl7C8oVr9GvdI1-K6a15DhKz1XOz9zkmhhryuxybo7LEVGiP-pitItKW-EEo0tq59IgBFWheYnSlBNDHiFUAyYIdEldkpt2zUWhZFfF82OAC56GLqAuDXpqP8LoLjS91UhCrx_fzBm