hSxHvI_HTbLGXaTgOLf7w3CwJ3uiC3bw8FEHgPmvuvJiPkmoCzDX5HT4fC8z5eQuxl-vikykmwCf5-yNtj9So8EwubNlP4ZJRY_8BCw_K-3LOeq2UUUVOFCRM3BeIJgGFMjlSE_dPeDIQCAZ4FrlqaTHqoMfMLU-r_70r2DaqGT32aDtzAILsmL0CQx-0JALSxxqYgrbnbwn6Y-CwekSgDJcUQ8H4CfLi43zs1rnEI21ynkF82fkS9WiDwSZ-qSL5pFBbz95cDK_Fzm373fOwqwdE=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Scala visibility**\\n\\nI'm considering whether to test via `scalac`, even though I’m instructed not to compile or run tests. I want to understand the rules around private members in Scala. For instance, a private method like `foo` in class `C` doesn't get mangled. But if I have `private[C]`, could it become something like `C$$foo`? Hm, private to a class does allow access to the companion object, which complicates things. I should check with `javap` how access works under the hood.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Understanding method visibility in Scala**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how private methods in a class are accessed only by that class, so why would the compiler expand method names to something like `Foo$$method`? I've noticed with `javap` that private methods might show differently. Name expansion seems to prevent issues with overriding if a subclass has the same method name. I remember Scala compiles private methods with a prefix, like `C$$foo`, to avoid potential conflicts. It all connects with protecting method integrity in inheritance.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_Tnm1u1JWMDqcqNTHPUJgTw1e|fc_00fbe55c2a84c5560169fa3ca7e8e481929e4d67d6cb560244", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala-reflect/2.11.8/src/test/scala/org_scala_lang/scala_reflect/JavaMirrorsInnerJavaMirrorTest.scala", "edits": [{"oldText": "    val packageScopedMethod = instanceMirror.reflectMethod(\n      singleMethod(nestedType, newTermName(\"packageScopedMethod\"))\n    )\n    assertThat(packageScopedMethod(\"suffix\").asInstanceOf[String]).isEqualTo(\"changed-suffix\")\n  }\n", "newText": "    val